  "risk_regime": {
    "stance": "risk_on",
    "conviction": 66,
    "rationale": "Six of ten members are explicitly risk_on (Ali 85, Guy 82, Chris 80, Eddy 75, Scott 70, Daren 65), three neutral (Jason 60, Miles 58, Tim 30), and one no_view (Justin 15). The weighted center of gravity is risk_on, but with deliberately moderate conviction for two reasons. First, this is structural, technology-and-adoption optimism ('still early', 'build through the winter'), NOT a tactical near-term price call \u2014 most members never discuss prices, cycles, or the FTX collapse. Second, the members closest to markets and policy (Jason, Miles) are tactically GUARDED post-FTX, emphasizing capital discipline, survival, fraud risk, and a hostile regulatory environment, while the researchers (Tim, Justin) express no market view at all. Net house posture: long-horizon constructive, near-term cautious.",
    "provenance": "extrapolated"
  },
  "notes": "Consensus weights coverage x conviction x stance-agreement. DOMINANT (broad + high + aligned): ZK, broad web3, L2 scaling, DeFi, gaming, and ETH (7/10, the desk anchor). CONTESTED \u2014 flagged as split and damped toward neutral, NOT carried as clean convictions: (1) NFT \u2014 5 members, mean ~72, but stance_dispersion 0.80: bullish on NFTs as a durable new asset class (Chris, Scott, Daren, Miles-licensing) yet with real bearish caveats (Daren on mint-revenue misalignment, Scott on speculation/mispricing being 'risky at any price'). Net: structurally constructive, conviction held down to ~50-55 by the split. (2) governance-DAO \u2014 5 members but dispersion 0.80: bullish on coordination potential (Ali, Chris, Guy) vs. concern over undiversified treasuries (Daren) and unwrapped-DAO legal liability (Miles). Treated as net-mild-bullish/contested, not a strong conviction. (3) MEV (dispersion 1.0), recursive-SNARKs (1.0), dao-legal-entities (1.0), and BTC (1.0, Miles bullish-on-decentralization vs. Tim bearish-on-PoW-guarantees) are genuinely SPLIT and deliberately omitted from the excited/concerned lists or held neutral \u2014 surfacing them as convictions would misrepresent the desk. FADED OUT (lone, low-to-moderate conviction): single-coverage tokens (stETH, MKR, AR, AXS, DAI, FRAX, ENS, cryptopunks, SOL, SHIB, SOS) and many single-member sector views; the strongest lone HIGH-conviction items (decentralization 95, wallet-infrastructure 87, consensus-protocol-design 88, regulation-by-enforcement 92, cex-proof-of-reserves 90) were retained thematically but at reduced consensus conviction to reflect their thin coverage. A consistent cross-desk caveat: most members are builders/researchers/lawyers, not allocators, so 'excitement' and 'concern' reflect technology and design conviction, not price targets \u2014 explaining the structural horizon on nearly every item and the extrapolated risk regime. No items were invented; all names reuse members' exact item names."
